Leave your comments below.

192
00:09:52,470 --> 00:09:54,829
And now it’s time to answer a question from
a fan

193
00:09:54,829 --> 00:09:58,480
who helps us keep making controversial episodes
like this,

194
00:09:58,480 --> 00:10:01,569
through supporting us on the crowdfunding
website Patreon:

195
00:10:01,569 --> 00:10:03,790
Ben asks:

196
00:10:03,790 --> 00:10:06,139
Have there been any attempts by the CCP,

197
00:10:06,139 --> 00:10:08,449
whether cyber attack’s or other means,

198
00:10:08,449 --> 00:10:11,480
to shut down or limit the protestor’s use
of telegram

199
00:10:11,480 --> 00:10:13,600
or other communications means?

200
00:10:13,600 --> 00:10:15,309
Good question, Ben.

201
00:10:15,309 --> 00:10:17,069
And the answer is: Yes.

202
00:10:17,069 --> 00:10:19,100
They’ve tried to hack Telegram.

203
00:10:19,100 --> 00:10:20,589
And they’ve almost certainly had agents

204
00:10:20,589 --> 00:10:22,160
trying to monitor all the chats.

205
00:10:22,160 --> 00:10:23,740
But that being said,

206
00:10:23,740 --> 00:10:25,980
there’s not much they can do when Hong Kong

207
00:10:25,980 --> 00:10:28,940
still has a free press and open internet.

208
00:10:28,940 --> 00:10:31,410
Of course, there’s a solution to *that*:

209
00:10:31,410 --> 00:10:35,509
The Emergency Regulations Ordinance of 1922.

210
00:10:35,509 --> 00:10:38,720
That would give the Hong Kong Chief Executive
broad powers,

211
00:10:38,720 --> 00:10:42,230
including the power to completely censor the
press—

212
00:10:42,230 --> 00:10:45,100
and probably the internet as well.

213
00:10:45,100 --> 00:10:49,149
But it’s such a nuclear option that they’re
unlikely to use it.

214
00:10:49,149 --> 00:10:50,149
At least right now.

215
00:10:50,149 --> 00:10:52,399
Thanks for your question, Ben.

216
